cological community.* Identifies chaparral’s common plants, animals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and insects * Features 79 color illustrations, 56 black-and-white photographs, and 3 maps* Examines the role of humans and fire in chaparral, covering the placement and design of homes, landscaping, and public policy  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChaparral ecologyzCalifornia. 0aChaparralzCalifornia. 7aNATURE / Plants / General.2bisacsh  acalifornia chaparral.  acalifornia landscape.  acalifornia.  achaparral ecology.  acommon plants and animals.  adrought resistant.  aecological communities.  aecologists.  aenvironment.  afield guide.  afire beetles.  afire tolerant.  aflora and fauna.  aillustrated.  akangaroo rats.  alizards.  amovie and tv plants.  anatural history.  aorganisms.  aplants and animals.  apublic lands.  aregional ecology.  aregional history.  aregional plant life.  aresilient ecology.  aseed germination.  atextbooks.1 aKeeley, Sterling, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093900440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939004423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939004/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles